[[File:Novelty Automation.jpg|thumb|Novelty Automation]]

'''Novelty Automation''' is an [[amusement arcade]] of satirical game machines in [[Holborn]], London.<ref name="wired">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/london-attractions-destinations-history|title=To mark London History Day, we list the capital's best hidden treasures|first=|last=WIRED|publisher=}}</ref> The machines are constructed by cartoonist and engineer [[Tim Hunkin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boingboing.net/2015/07/06/robotic-dog-pants-dribbles-wa.html|title=Robotic dog pants, dribbles warm saliva, and tries to bite you / Boing Boing|website=boingboing.net}}</ref> often by hand,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/culture/gaming/a16334/novelty-automation-arcade/|title=At This Arcade, You Play to Stop a Nuclear Meltdown|date=7 July 2015|publisher=}}</ref> and the arcade includes an expressive photo booth, an interactive divorce and a "[[Large hadron collider|small hadron collider]]".<ref name="wired"/> The arcade also includes three of Hunkin's machines which were once on display at [[Cabaret Mechanical Theatre]]'s Covent Garden exhibition: ''The Frisker'', ''Test Your Nerve'' and ''The Chiropodist''.<ref name="cab">{{cite web|url=http://cabaret.co.uk/novelty-automation/|title=Novelty Automation|date=28 January 2015|publisher=Cabaret Mechanical Theatre}}</ref>

Discussing the venue's ''Housing Ladder'' [[slot machine]], in which a player walks on [[treadmill]] steps on a physical ladder in order to move an automated figure towards a model house, Hunkin has said "I don’t think political art has an enormous effect, but in the short term it is satisfying to reinforce people’s disrespect of the villains."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/nov/17/housing-ladder-arcade-game-has-players-dodging-buy-to-let-investors|title=Housing Ladder arcade game has players dodging buy-to-let investors|first=Matthew|last=Weaver|date=17 November 2016|website=the Guardian}}</ref>

The arcade opened in February 2015.<ref name="cab"/>

